Anonymous Thu 15 Jul 2021 01:57:14 No.40178162 Report
Quoted By: >>40181584
>>40177817
The way I usually judge a story/scene/chapter is that I should have an idea really soon after I start of two of the three: beginning, middle & end.
The worst for me is having a beginning and end, but little idea of how to get from one end to the other.
But my advice is just to keep writing. The more scenes you do, the easier it gets to feel what has to happen in that unknown third time period.

So let's take the school shooter one
Where/how/when did they meet?
What do they have in common, and what not?
What's her home life? His?
Her least favorite school subject?
Describe her clothing. Describe her outside, both in bright sunshine and in a tree's shade. Find a good dichotomy for him and do that too.
What's one thing she'd never want another person to know, and why? How would it impact her if he found out? How would he react?
Give three differences between her outward persona and her inner thoughts.

If you can't develop a character because they won't stop talking to you, prod them until the story behind the story comes out.
Writing is like detective work. Everyone's hiding something.
